es. Drawing on sources ranging from art to medical treatises, fiction, and funerary writings, they separate out the many complexities in the Chinese cultural construction of childhood and the ways it has changed over time. Listening to how Chinese talked about children--whether their own child, the abstract child in need of education or medical care, the ideal precocious child, or the fictional child--lets us assess in concrete terms the structures and values that underlay Chinese life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChildrenzChinaxHistory. 0aChildrenzChinaxSocial conditions. 0aYouthzChinaxHistory. 0aYouthzChinaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aDewoskin, Kenneth J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFurth, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHung, Wu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenney, Anne B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKinney, Anne Behnke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeung, Angela Ki Che, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLupher, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMather, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Lucien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPease, Catherine E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSommerville, C. John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaltner, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWu, Pei-Yi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package: